{{short description|Legendary horse-like creature with a large horn projecting from forehead}}
{{Infobox mythical creature
|name = Unicorn
|image = DomenichinounicornPalFarnese.jpg
|caption = ''The gentle and pensive maiden has the power to tame the unicorn,'' fresco by [[Domenichino]], c. 1604–05 ([[Palazzo Farnese|Palazzo Farnese, Rome]])&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://catalogo.fondazionezeri.unibo.it/scheda.v2.jsp?tipo_scheda=OA&amp;id=58897 |work=Fondazione Federico Zeri, University of Bologna |title=Zampieri Domenico, Madonna e unicorno}}&lt;/ref&gt;
|Grouping = Mythology
|Sub_Grouping =
|AKA = [[Monoceros (mythology)|Monocerus]]
|Similar_creatures = [[Qilin]], [[Re'em]], [[Indrik]], [[Shadhavar]], [[Camahueto]], [[Karkadann]]
|Mythology = Worldwide
}}
[[File:Oftheunicorn.jpg|thumb|Of the Unicorn]]
The '''unicorn''' is a [[legendary creature]] that has been described since [[Classical antiquity|antiquity]] as a beast with a single large, pointed, spiraling [[horn (anatomy)|horn]] projecting from its forehead. The unicorn was depicted in ancient seals of the [[Indus Valley Civilization]] and was mentioned by the [[Ancient Greece|ancient Greeks]] in accounts of [[natural history]] by various writers, including [[Ctesias]], [[Strabo]], [[Pliny the Younger]], [[Claudius Aelianus|Aelian]]&lt;ref name=Britannica&gt;{{cite book|title=The Encyclopædia Britannica: A Dictionary of Arts, Sciences, Literature and General Information|year=1911|volume=27|page=581}}&lt;/ref&gt; and [[Cosmas Indicopleustes]].&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=http://www.documentacatholicaomnia.eu/04z/z_0500-0600__Cosmas_Indicopleustis__Christiana_Topographia_(MPG_088_0051_0476)__GM.pdf.html|title=Cosmas Indicopleustis - Christiana Topographia (MPG 088 0051 0476) [0500-0600] Full Text at Documenta Catholica Omnia|website=www.documentacatholicaomnia.eu}}&lt;/ref&gt; The [[Bible]] also describes an animal, the [[re'em]], which some versions translate as ''unicorn''.&lt;ref name=&quot;Britannica&quot; /&gt;

In European folklore, the unicorn is often depicted as a white [[horse]]-like or [[goat]]-like animal with a long horn, cloven hooves, and sometimes a goat's beard. In the [[Middle Ages]] and [[Renaissance]], it was commonly described as an extremely wild [[forest|woodland]] creature, a symbol of purity and grace, which could be captured only by a virgin. In the encyclopedias, its horn was said to have the power to render poisoned water potable and to heal sickness. In medieval and Renaissance times, the tusk of the [[narwhal]] was sometimes sold as unicorn horn.

The unicorn continues to hold a place in popular culture. It is often used as a symbol of fantasy or rarity.&lt;ref&gt;[https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/unicorn Unicorn], Merriam-Webster Dictionary.&lt;/ref&gt;

== History ==
=== In antiquity ===
[[File:Indus civilisation seal unicorn at Indian Museum, Kolkata.jpg|thumb|Unicorn seal of Indus Valley, [[Indian Museum]], India]]
A number of seals seemingly depicting unicorns have been found from the [[Indus Valley Civilization]].&lt;ref&gt;[https://web.archive.org/web/20011111160249/http://www.geocities.com/pak_history/Harappan.html Discussion of the Indus Valley Civilization with mention of unicorn seals]&lt;/ref&gt; Seals with such a design are thought to be a mark of high [[social rank]].&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=https://www.harappa.com/seal/seal1.html|title=A Unicorn Seal|website=www.harappa.com}}&lt;/ref&gt; These have also been interpreted as representations of [[aurochs]]—a type of large wild cattle that formerly inhabited Europe, Asia and North Africa—or derivatives of aurochs, because the animal is always shown in profile, indicating there may have been another horn, which is not seen in profile.&lt;ref&gt;Geer, Alexandra Anna Enrica van der (2008). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=oQ3quxh9gsgC Animals in stone: Indian mammals sculptured through time]''. Brill, Leiden. {{ISBN|90-04-16819-2}}. pp. 112-114.&lt;/ref&gt;

Unicorns are not found in [[Greek mythology]], but rather in the accounts of [[natural history]], for Greek writers of natural history were convinced of the reality of unicorns, which they believed lived in India, a distant and fabulous realm for them. The earliest description is from [[Ctesias]], who in his book ''[[Indica (Ctesias)|Indika]]'' (&quot;On [[India]]&quot;) described them as [[Onager|wild ass]]es, fleet of foot, having a horn a [[cubit]] and a half ({{Convert|700|mm|in|disp = comma|abbr = in}}) in length, and colored white, red and black.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book
|last = Ctesias {{color|black|(390 BC)}}
|authorlink = Ctesias
|title = Indica (Τα Ἰνδικά)
|date =
|chapter = 45
|url = https://www.livius.org/ct-cz/ctesias/photius_indica.html}} (quoted by [[Photios I of Constantinople|Photius]])&lt;/ref&gt;

[[File:Unicorn in Apadana, Shush, Iran--2017-10.jpg|thumb|Unicorn in [[Apadana]], [[Susa|Shush]], Iran]]

Ctesias got his information while living in [[Persian Empire|Persia]]. Unicorns on a relief sculpture have been found at the ancient Persian capital of [[Persepolis]] in Iran.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book|title=Unicorns and Other Magical Creatures|last=Hamilton|first=John|publisher=ABDO Publishing Company|year=2010|isbn=978-1617842818|location=|pages=}}&lt;/ref&gt;  [[Aristotle]] must be following Ctesias when he mentions two one-horned animals, the [[oryx]] (a kind of [[antelope]]) and the so-called &quot;Indian ass&quot; (ἰνδικὸς ὄνος).&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book
