[[Antigonus of Carystus]] also wrote about the  one-horned &quot;Indian ass&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;[https://sites.google.com/site/paradoxography/texts/antigonus Antigonus, Compilation of Marvellous Accounts, 66]&lt;/ref&gt;
[[Strabo]] says that in the [[Caucasus]] there were one-horned horses with stag-like heads.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book
|last = Strabo {{color|black|(before 24 AD)}}
|authorlink = Strabo
|title = Geography
|date = 
|chapter = Book 15. Chapter 1. Section 56.
|url = http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/15A3*.html }}&lt;/ref&gt;
[[Pliny the Elder]] mentions the oryx and an Indian [[ox]] (perhaps a [[rhinoceros]]) as one-horned beasts, as well as &quot;a very fierce animal called the monoceros which has the head of the [[Deer|stag]], the feet of the [[elephant]], and the tail of the [[boar]], while the rest of the body is like that of the horse; it makes a deep lowing noise, and has a single black horn, which projects from the middle of its forehead, two cubits [{{Convert|900|mm|in|disp = comma|abbr = in}}] in length.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book
 |last       = Pliny {{color|black|(77 AD)}}
 |authorlink = Pliny the Elder
 |others     = trans. John Bostock
 |title      = Natural History
 |date       = 
 |chapter    = Book 8, Chapter 31
